# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1923-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1923-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1923-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1923-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1923-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1923-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1923-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1923-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1923-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1923-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1923-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1923-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1923-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1923-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The **1923 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1923 season.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The 20th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees against the National League (NL) champion New York Giants.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The Yankees beat the Giants in six games.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] This would be the first of the Yankees' 27 World Series championships (as of 2026).
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The series was not played in a 2–3–2 format: as with the previous two Series (where both clubs had shared the Polo Grounds) the home field alternated each game, though this time it involved switching ballparks, as the first Yankee Stadium had opened this season.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The Yankees opened their new stadium in April on a home run by Babe Ruth, setting the tone for the season and this Series, in which Ruth hit three home runs along with drawing eight walks.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] In Game 2, second baseman, Aaron Ward hit a home run.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The Giants' one bright spot was "Old Casey" Stengel, who hit game-winning homers in each of the two Giants' victories.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] In typically eccentric Stengel fashion, one of them was inside-the-park at the cavernous Yankee Stadium, and his shoe came loose during his run around the bases.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Stengel was traded after the season, leading him to quip later in life, "It's a good thing I didn't hit *three* homers in *three* games, or McGraw would have traded me to the Three-I League!".
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] A quarter century later, Stengel would take on the role of Yankees manager, and would guide the Bronx Bombers through one of their most successful eras.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] In Game 6, the Yankees overcame a 4–1 deficit by staging a five-run rally in the eighth inning to clinch the series.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) marked the only time (as of 2024), that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Brothers Bob and Irish Meusel played against each other in each of those three series, making them the first set of brothers to play against each other on opposing teams in a World Series or any Big Four championship series.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Thanks to the large seating capacity of the new Yankee Stadium, coupled with expansion of the Polo Grounds the same year, the 1923 Series was the first to eclipse 300,000 in total attendance (301,430), averaging over 50,000 per game (50,238), with gate receipts over $1 million ($1,063,815.00).
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] This was the third time that a team had inaugurated a new stadium with a World Series win, and would be the last until the St.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Louis Cardinals victory in their new ballpark in 2006, and the New York Yankees again won the World Series in 2009 in their new Yankee Stadium.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Babe Ruth had a great series, his first one as a Yankee, batting .368 and hitting three home runs in the series.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Neither Lou Gehrig, Bill Terry nor Hack Wilson played in the Series.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] These future Hall of Famers were each in their first season and had played no more than thirteen games in the regular season.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Gehrig had been called up from Hartford to play for the Yankees that year.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] In that time, however, a team had to have the permission of both the commissioner and the opposing team's manager to make a roster change so late in the season eligible for postseason play.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The Yankees gained the permission of Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis who then told them to get John McGraw's permission.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] McGraw and the Yankees had a long history of disdain after both teams had shared a stadium and the Giants had won both the 1921 and 1922 World Series from New York.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Therefore, he declined permission and Gehrig would not be allowed to participate in the series which otherwise would have been his first World Series.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] A ninth-inning inside-the-park homer by Casey Stengel beat the Yankees on their home field.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Babe Ruth scored in the first inning on a Bob Meusel double.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Yankee center fielder Whitey Witt's two-run single in the next inning made it 3-0.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] The Giants fought back with a four-run third, knocking out Yankee starter Waite Hoyt from the game.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] It was tied at 4-4 in the ninth inning until Casey came to bat, legging out a long drive to the left-center gap.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] After trading home runs by Aaron Ward and Irish Meusel, a pair of Babe Ruth blasts in the fourth and fifth innings turned out to be the difference.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] A scoreless pitching duel lasted until the seventh inning, when Casey Stengel struck again, this time with a homer that left the park.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] It gave Art Nehf the win over Sad Sam Jones, despite the Giants getting just four hits.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] A six-run second inning chased Giant starter Jack Scott, the first four Yankee batters of that inning reaching safely.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] A ninth-inning leadoff inside-the-park homer by Ross Youngs gave the home team a flicker of hope, but Herb Pennock mopped up in relief.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Bob Meusel's two-run triple and a Wally Pipp sacrifice fly made it 3-0.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Then the Yankees got four more in the second, Joe Dugan's three-run inside-the-park homer the big blow.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Bullet Joe Bush surrendered just three hits to the Giants, who now faced elimination.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Right off the bat, the Yankees struck with a Babe Ruth two-out homer in the first.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] But then the Giants and their Polo Grounds crowd came to life.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Three singles in the first tied the score.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Center fielder Bill Cunningham knocked in a go-ahead run in the fourth, followed by catcher Frank Snyder's homer in the fifth inning.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Down 4-1, the Yankees took advantage of two singles followed by 3 consecutive walks.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Ruth struck out with the score 4-3, and Bob Meusel hit a clutch two-out single scoring two runs, and a third scoring on an error, making it 6-4 Yankees.
[src:1923-world-series/1923-world-series] Sad Sam Jones would get the 6 out save to win the Yankees their first championship.
[src:1923-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1923-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
